      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The irate readers have it, with five letters last week damning Steven Rinella for cruelty to animals for killing sparrows and squirrels (little mention was made of bigger game).</p>
        <p>Sorry, but I didn't see it that way. ''Thumping with a hammer'' seemed to me a quick and painless death for animals that are in oversupply (especially the sparrows that arrived here from England and displaced so many of our native birds) thanks to all that food supplied by humans.</p>
        <p>The real animal cruelty lies in the feedlots and cramped prisons in which the vast majority of our meat animals are raised. Unlike most readers of The Times, I've visited factory farms and slaughterhouses, and I'd rather eat hunted game than animals kept under the brutal regimes that are hidden from consumer view.</p>
        <p>It's not Mr. Rinella who has usurped animals' freedom, it's the consumers of supermarket beef, chicken and pork.</p>
        <p>Susan Goldhor  Cambridge, Mass.</p>
      </block>
